        "user": "How does \"elastic automator\" differ from RPA bot?",
        "assistant": "Good question — this contrast is sharper than the agent one, because RPA and elastic automators sit on opposite sides of a real technical divide.\n\n### Core difference: how they handle uncertainty\n\n- **RPA bot**: follows a *predefined, deterministic script*. Click here, read this field, copy to that system. Input variation breaks it.\n- **Elastic automator** (per your definition): *absorbs* input variation by using an LLM to convert fuzzy input into executable structure on the fly.\n\nRPA is rigid automation. Elastic automation is, well, elastic.\n\n### Point-by-point comparison\n\n| Dimension | RPA bot | Elastic automator |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Input** | Must be structured/predictable | Tolerates vague, natural-language, messy input |\n| **Logic** | Hand-authored rules and flows | Generated by an LLM at runtime |\n| **Failure mode** | Breaks on unexpected input | Degrades gracefully — produces *something* plausible |\n| **Correction** | Requires a developer to update the script | Self-corrects within its own loop |\n| **Determinism** | Deterministic, auditable | Stochastic, harder to audit |\n| **Trust basis** | \"It does exactly what we wrote\" | \"The output *appears* intelligent\" |\n\n### The key philosophical difference\n\nRPA's honesty is structural: you can read the script and know what it will do. Its limits are visible.\n\nAn elastic automator's competence is *manufactured by iteration*. The loop polishes outputs until they look right. This is more powerful on ambiguous tasks, but the \"appears intelligent\" hedge in your definition matters here — you can't inspect a script to know what it will do, only observe whether the output looks acceptable.\n\n### Where they're converging\n\nModern \"intelligent automation\" or \"agentic RPA\" products (UiPath with LLMs, Automation Anywhere's AI features, etc.) are essentially bolting elastic-automator behavior onto RPA backbones — using LLMs for the fuzzy front-end (reading emails, interpreting requests) and deterministic RPA for the back-end (clicking through SAP). So the categories are blending in practice, even though they're conceptually distinct.\n\n### One-line summary\n\n**RPA bot**: rigid script that fails on ambiguity.\n**Elastic automator**: LLM loop that consumes ambiguity and outputs something that looks competent.\n\nThe trade is the same trade you see everywhere with LLMs: flexibility and apparent intelligence in exchange for determinism and auditability.",
